segments.text: An interview with Brigadier General Mike Kokonos.
Today is Monday, 1st of June.
This is Terry Anderson.
Let's start by asking where and when you were born.
I was born in Beaumont, Texas, February the 2nd, 1920.
General Kokonos prefers Mike P. Kokonos.
Why do you prefer P?
Because it's my daddy's name, Pete.
Okay, Pete.
Tell me about your father.
I like to be identified with my daddy.
Okay, tell me about your father.
Papa...
Papa came to Beaumont, Texas around 1909 from Greece.
And he's...
Whereabouts in Greece?
He's from Parga, Greece.
P-A-R-G-A.
It's the northwest part of Greece.
Macedonia?
No, no, Peloponnesus.
Yeah, Peloponnesus, or Carfu, near Carfu, the island of Carfu.
And he came to Beaumont and opened up a restaurant
And then he stayed here a year or two, and then he went back to Greece and married Mama and brought Mama back to Beaumont.
And this is where we have stayed and lived ever since they came to Texas.
Now, when he came, why Texas?
He had a friend from his hometown who worked at LaBelle, Texas.
He worked on a ranch.
And he told Papa to come on and work with us.
And when Papa got here, he didn't like working out there as a cowboy.
So he came into Beaumont.
La Belle is about five miles outside of Beaumont.
Did he keep the restaurant for his entire life?
No.
Can you tell me about that?
Yes, he kept the restaurant for several years.
And then the children began to come, my older brother,

GP Coconuts and Jimmy and myself and he then opened up a grocery store a confectionary type by the old baseball park on Magnolia Street and we lived behind the grocery store or confectionary and we lived behind it and
And he had the restaurant and the confectionery.
And then the Depression hit about 26, well, 29, somewhere along in there.
And he lost the restaurant and kept the grocery store.
And we were all raised behind this grocery store, my three brothers and sister, Helen and Andrew and Jimmy and GP, Janess.
And then he had that for a while.
And when he lost it, he got into the bread business.
He was a bread salesman.
Oh, really?
For a company, or did he have his own?
No, for Purity Bakery.
It was a company here in Beaumont, and he sold bread and rolls, hot dog rolls and hamburger rolls to the rest of us, and we used to go as kids to help him do that.
We'd get up in the morning around 2, 33 o'clock in the morning and help Papa pack the rolls in the truck from the hot ovens.
This is during the Depression?
During the Depression, 29, 30, 31, and
And we would make the rounds with him to all the restaurants and grocery stores that he had and help him deliver the rolls and deliver the bread, French bread.
And he kept that for a while and then we finally, we had to give up the grocery store.
It just got too bad.
We couldn't handle it anymore and then we moved into another, right around- In other words, you weren't making enough money to make it work?
Money to make the grocery store work.
And so we,
We moved right, just right around the corner, half a block away on Hazel Street, 947 Hazel Street.
And to this day, we all still own that property.
And my brother, Janice, has his oil office there.
He's an independent oil operator.
Remodeled it and fixed it up.
Now, I'm wondering about your father's education.
Papa, Papa finished high school in one year
of college in Greece.
And then that's the reason we're all graduates of A&M, because he insisted that we go to college.
It was his driving force that led us to A&M.
And A&M, he really picked A&M because it was a military school.
It was conservative type.
school, which is his thinking.
He was a conservative type person, and he... Conservative in what way?
Conservative in not, well, in his love for this country.
He thought America was the greatest country in the world, do anything for it, and he felt that we would...
He never had a longing then to go back to Greece?
Never.
He loved it.
Except to marry.
Just to marry and get mom and bring her back here.
Mm-hmm.
And after he brought her back here, brought her back to Beaumont, he then went about raising a family.
And we were instilled by him, the discipline of running a... Oh, you don't want to stay around here?
No, baby, it's on TV.
It's on tape.
Oh, that's okay.
We'll just erase anything.
I wasn't even there.
He was a person who kept a low profile, but yet he was strong-willed and he maintained discipline in the family.
So in other words, you're defining him as a conservative, as a man who loves his
his country was strong-willed and it was a disciplinarian.
Disciplinarian, right.
And he loved the old country ideas and he thought A&M was that way.
I see, yeah.
See, and because he, we were, I know, I remember as a little kid that people come talk to Papa about, well,
Why don't you send him to some other schools?
Send my older brother.
See, he was in, he was the one that first went to A&M.
And he had gone to, my brother Pete, Janelle, had gone to some, he'd gone to, let's see, a couple other schools just to visit.
And he hitched tight.
And he'd come back home and he would tell Papa what they looked like and what the schools were all about.
And Papa said, well, A&M sounds like the school I'd like to see my sons go to.
And so...
It's military.
It means it would help you become a good citizen by being, participating in the military, and just been there.
And so that's how we were led to go to A&M.
Now, was he, was your father ever involved in the military, either in Greece or in America?
Yeah, he was involved in Greece when the Turkish
See, the Turkish rule in Greece, he was involved a little while then he left.
So he had a favorable idea of the military before he came to this country.
Right, yeah.
So he felt that the military helped him.
That's correct.
He felt the military helped him to help us.
So it was really passed on down to us from him by his training that he had in the military in Greece.
But he never talked much about it though.
When was that?
I don't know.
He just, of course we were kids growing up and he was too busy trying to make a living I guess and we never really talked much about it except military.
He liked the military.
How about the old country?
Did he talk much about what life was?
Did you ever ask your father about what it was like back in the old country?
He did.
Of course we were kids.
Papa died awfully young.
Yeah.
He died...
He was 58, and we were gone in the army when he died in 45.

He talked about life in the old country, but as kids, you know, it's hard to remember things that he would tell, but I remember one time he said, well, he says, it's a good thing we live in America, otherwise you might have been a goat herder, a goat tenderer.
He says, you'd have been a good one, because I'd have made you a good one, you know.
But that was another thing he liked about America then, the mobility.
Mobility and the opportunities that we had here.
Yeah.
Yeah.
Just great opportunities.
But he liked the simple things of Greece, you know, the simple things in life.
He never dressed extravagantly.
Of course, he couldn't.
Things were tough.
Yeah, yeah.
And Mama was very prudent in her running the house.
I can remember when he was selling bread on the bread truck that he gave her 50 cents.
He said, now this is for today's meals.
And Mama would walk blocks to the A&P store and the grocery store.
We had a neighborhood grocery store, but she'd walk blocks to go to the grocery store to save a few pennies.
to buy, you know, beans or rice or whatever.
So she could make that 50 cents last the whole day.
And she could.
Oh, yeah.
And so... Could you tell me about her more, your mother?
Could you describe what type of person she was?
She was a small person, but she was... She loved to help people.
I never said anything like it.
She would walk blocks, miles.
Somebody was sick.
Yeah, especially her Greek friends that she knew.
She would walk to help them out and spend the day with them.
Even though we were at home, the kids were at home, she was willing to go out and help whatever need they needed.
And people liked her.
She spoke.
She understood English well, but she still
spoke with a Greek accent.
In our home, we had to talk Greek.
Really?
That's how we learned to speak Greek.
We'd talk Greek.
In fact, I can remember Mama saying to us in Greek, you're going to go to school and learn the English language, but we don't have any Greek school here, so I'm going to teach you Greek at home.
We're going to all talk Greek.
So we'd talk and get home.
And, of course, we would talk English to Mama, so she would learn how to speak English.
Of course, Papa spoke well.
He was very fluent in his English language and wrote well.
But she would make us talk Greek, so we would learn it.
And thank God we did, because that's the way we learned.
We learned how all of us speak Greek.
Who is the authority in the household?
The father.
Papa was.
He ran the house.
There was no question about it.
No question about it.
He was the boss.
And then, of course, he wasn't around.
Then the older brother was the authority.
My brother Janelle.
We call him Janelle.
It's GP.
He finished A&M in 38, petroleum engineering.
And then after Papa died in 45, the older brother steps in and takes over.
But he, but Papa was the boss.
Oh yeah.
So it was a traditional family structure then.
Right.
Almost molded on the old country, but modified.
By the American way of life.
Oh yeah, it was very traditional.
And we still try to maintain that today.

Speaking Greek, that's rather interesting because when my great-great-grandfather came over from Germany, one of the very first things on my mother's side, one of the very first things that my great-great-grandmother did was forbid the children to speak German because she wanted them to become Americans.
Americans speak American or English.
And so this is rather interesting that you spoke Greek at home.
Yeah, we did.
We spoke Greek at home with Mama
And, of course, Papa too didn't want us to lose that heritage that we had and traditions.
But yet, at the same time, Papa preached to us that he wanted us to be an American citizen and be a patriotic American citizen.
America comes first.
No second thoughts about Greece or anything like that.
America was first.
And this was his, he used to, of course, later on, he bought a dinner club out on the highway, and he would always greet the customers with, God bless America.
Really?
Yeah, and a little grease.
That's during the war, during the war in 1941 to 1945.
The Navy had a base in Orange, Texas, and so we had a lot of Navy personnel, and they traded with him and patronized his little dinner pub he had out there.
And people from Fort Polk used to come over.
Did he ever go back to Greece on a vacation?
Never did.
Neither did Mama.
Have you?
I have not.
Now, my brother has, and I was on the plane in Rome, Italy,
after the war when I was on occupation duty as a lieutenant.
And I was waiting on a plane in Rome to fly to Athens to go to Parga in Paxos, where my mother was from.
And I had my pass from the army and everything.
They authorized it because I was a blood kin.
They had a communist uprising.
And we were grounded and we couldn't get over there.
So it knocked me out.
And the only way you could get into Greece, because you know, Germany,
just dominated.
I mean, it just slaughtered all these people.
It was incredible what they did to Germany.
And of course, the Greeks put up a very strong fight with them.
And America, the United States Army's position was they didn't want any tourists going over there.
Of course, they were communists.
Well, it was devastating.
It was devastating.
Plus the Civil War.
Civil War.
See, they were the communists.
But when they found out, if they found out you had blood kin,
then you can get a special pass.
So I was on the plane at Rome.
I was sitting on the plane ready to go.
And I had not been, but my brother's family has been over there.
My sister's been there.
But that's interesting that you haven't been.
We talk about going.
But you've got seven kids, Terry.
Educating them, you know, it's pretty hard.
And so we were, we'd still think about going, and we are, we're going to go.
My son's been, my son pays class of 80 at A&M.
Went to Papa's church on Easter Sunday this past year.
He was over there, he took a, when he got out of A&M, he took the tour, backpacked it.
And when he stayed, he stayed in,
in Greece about six weeks.
And he celebrated Easter with my Papa's church and family over there.
Well, that brings me to another topic.
You've been the past president of the St. George Greek Orthodox Church here.
And I was wondering how or what role that religion played in your upbringing.
Well, it played a very strong
part in my life because we attended the Orthodox Church ever since we kept baptizing the church.
And it helped me in my military duties because I always regarded the chaplain as a key staff advisor.
And I always sought his advice and sought his guidance and commanding.
And be surprised.
The chaplains that I talked to were, you know, couldn't comprehend sometimes why my emphasis was always with them, because the previous commanders they had just kind of pushed them aside.
Yeah, pushed them aside.
Now, I didn't make a big, big splash about it.
It was always sort of just like my religions, very conservative and very traditional.
and very orthodox.
That's what we are, Greek orthodox.
And so I had the situation to earn me the same way.
It was always a very low-profile approach with the chaplain, but I emphasized his use.
And I was always, really, the chaplains always were kind of surprised that I would seek them.
But I did it not for myself.
for the unit or for the personnel.
And I was president five, six years of the church here.
And we have one church in the area, and it's in Port Offaly, Texas.
It's about 22 miles from here.
And I used to load my seven kids, and Catherine and I, and station away, and off we'd go every Sunday.
So it played, and then Papa.
Very important.
Papa was what we call a,
A lay reader in church.
Only we do it by chanting.
We sing.
I don't know if you've ever been to Greek Orthodoxy.
It's all singing.
The priests, the choir, and the chanters.
They chant the prayers.
Oh, really?
Yes, it's singing.
Papa was a Greek.
He did it in Greek while the choir would do it in English.
That's when I was a kid growing up.
And so that always left a strong impression on me.
So my whole family, my brothers, sisters, we all feel the same way about religion, very strong.
And it has played a very strong part in my life.
OK, I was wondering something else about your Greek heritage and the fact that you were an immigrant son.
Did you ever feel that you
were being discriminated against in this country?
I never felt it.
Even though as kids, we were the only Greeks in the block.
Yeah, I would imagine.
This area doesn't have a large population.
No, it really doesn't.
No, I didn't think so.
But I never felt discriminated, except when I got older.
Tell me about it.

I run across people who, I'm talking about maturity, 30, 35, 40 years old, and in the Army, who would, I got the feeling that people I was talking to, my superior officers, would kind of say, Greek, you know.
But as a young kid growing up, I never got that feeling.
But I guess it's because as you get older, it's very competitive, and it gets, you know,
people look for weaknesses in you.
See, and they try to probe your weakness.
And they thought maybe because I was of Greek heritage that that might be a weakness.
Actually, there was a stronger point in my life.
I was strong.
Because it was an inheritance that I had and it was mine.
And I just felt proud.
But yet at the same time, I was a
you know, American citizen, born and raised here.
Did your father ever complain?
Never.
Papa never complained.
You never said anything about that?
No, I never heard Papa complain about it at all.
At all.
And neither did Mama.
Of course, Mama wasn't in the civic world like Papa was.
Never complained.
But that's interesting that you realize this in the military because the military in this country has been...

Well, it's been a part of society, which has taken all types, all races, colors, and creeds, and put them into one big pot, sort of the melting pot idea, and really outlawed discrimination or racism, like what Truman did for the blacks in the military, by integrating it, and really... Well, the ethnic composure of a person, it's just, you...
in life, you run across a few people who resent the fact that, you know, they're not the same ethnic race as you.
And I, like I said, I didn't feel this until I was older.
A&M loved us.
Man, it was just, you know, talk about a melting pot.
A&M was a melting pot, you know.
And there was no discrimination there at all, never.
In fact, they never called me Greek in the A&M.
It was always Coke or Cokie or Mike.
In the Army, later on, I was referred to as, oh, yeah, that Greek major down there.
See, that's what I was telling you about.
Sure.
Because, or that Greek colonel.
Because we're battalion commanders in the same division.
You know, you compete.
units against unit, and commanders against commander.
It's a competition.
And Kidwell will tell you this.
See, I served with Kidwell for 70 years.
He was my artillery commander.
But this is where, this is an example I'm going to use.
Okay.
Let's talk for a minute about your siblings, your brothers and your sisters and your family.
How did you get along with them?
Great.
Yes, great.
No question about it.
My older brother was the leader, and he was the boss among the brothers.
But we got along fine.
We all lived together.
Lived in one room.
And we, for a while, we all lived in one bed.
Slept in one bed.
The brothers and sister had one little room.
We were a very modest means of living.
A house behind a big street.
I can imagine the depression.
Yeah, it was tough.
And we lived in bed.
And then one day, Popper bought another bed.
And so we split up.
My older brother and I slept together, and Jimmy, who was next to the oldest, and Andrew, my younger brother, slept together.
And then when we moved around the corner to the big house that had one, two, three bedrooms, we thought we were having this ride.
And so we all grew up playing with each other and defending each other at the Y. YMCA was a very important part of my life.
My brother's wife.
Why don't we explain that, Tom?
Well, I lived about two blocks from the Y.
And we used to go down to the Y as kids, 10, 11 years old.
And that's where we learned to swim and play football and basketball.
In fact, that's where I learned to play basketball.
They got me my basketball scholarship at A&M.
Really?
Yeah.
It's at the Y.
And when we had little problems among the kids, you know, we want to fight, it was always the four coconuts against whoever wanted to fight us.
And we sold newspapers on the street together.

We would, downtown Beaumont, we'd get up in the mornings around 4.30, and we'd go down and grab about 10 newspapers, Beaumont Enterprise, and we'd go down the corner, like the Edson Hotel corner, and try to, because there was more traffic there, and we'd try to sell the papers.
And the other newspaper boys would try to come chase us all.
Well, I just followed them.
That's right.
I had to chase all the brothers off.
We'd fight them.
Then my brother, Janelle, would go to the Fuller Cafe corner.
That was another one.
And the bigger boys would want to jump in.
Well, boy, we'd all run down there, and first thing you know, we were fighting these newspaper boys.
So we all grew up together as one.
Real close.
Real close.
Very close knit.
And even today, we go to dances together, we go to parties together, we go to socials together, and funerals together.
A friend of ours, we all go together wherever we go.
Honor the governor of Texas, we all go together.
How about rivalry?
Did you have much rivalry, or was it more of a learning, or was it more of a situation?
Not like I had a lot of rivalry with my brother.
It's normal.
Yeah, I guess, yeah, it was a little rivalry.
More so, I guess, because Andrew, my younger brother, and I were close.
Because we were in junior high and high school together, and we participated in a basketball team.
And so there was a little rivalry there.
Swimming team down at the Y. Andrew and I.
But there wasn't much rivalry between my older brother, because they were a little older than we were, and Jimmy.
Jimmy and I boxed together.
He was in high school.
By the way, he was a Golden Cup champ.
Years ago, my brother Jim and his former marital...
He used you for his punching bag?
He used me for his punching bag.

I was in junior high and he was in high school, and I used to go with the Beaumont High School boxing team to different cities, Louisiana, Houston, Galveston, and they didn't have anybody small enough to fight him, so they used me.
So we would fight.
We were always close, and we'd see who could beat each other.
That's about it.
But as far as rivalry, it was just a very friendly rival type thing.
Now, you've had, there's no doubt about it, you've had a very successful career.
In what way do you think your parents are responsible for that?
In teaching us self-discipline.
Self-discipline.
And teaching us...
how to get along with people.
It's just, Papa was, especially Mama, Mama talked to us about home life, families, and to get along.
But I think the biggest thing,
self-discipline and to work.
Just work.
A work ethic.
Just the idea of working.
You work.
Whatever you need, you have to work for.
You can't just expect people to hand you something.
Because all my brothers worked.
Even my sister.
They're all very successful, grown people now.
They worked at it.
Everybody worked.
Nobody...
Hard workers.
Hard workers, and loved their country.
Papa, boy, he'd talk to us about love of America all the time.
But I think the thing was self-discipline and work and honesty, be honest.
That's it.
Let's move on then to your education.
Can you tell me about your early years?
Sure.
I went to Millard Elementary School.
First through the... Millard?
M-I-L-L-A-R-D. Millard Elementary School, which was in the neighborhood about four blocks from, five blocks from where we lived.
And that was through the first through the fifth grade.
And then went to Dick Dowling Junior High
And it was, uh, uh, Millard was east where we live, and Dowling was, uh, Dick Dowling was west.
Is that what his name?
Dick Dowling, junior high.
Yeah, they, Dick Dowling.
The road here?
Oh, Dowling?
No, that's D-O-W-L-A.
Dick Dowling was a great Texas hero.
Uh, he, uh, fought for the independence of Texas.
Along with Bowie and Travis and, oh yeah, David Crockett.
We have two junior high schools here.
One was named David Crockett, and that was in the south end, and Dick Dowling, which was in the north end where we lived north, sort of north end of Bowman.
And then I went to Bowman High School, 11 grades.
Bowman High at that time had only 11 grades.
Really?
That's right.
And not 12?
Not 12.
Why was that?
I don't know.
They just changed 12 here, what, maybe 15 years ago.
It had not always been 12.
It was 11.
So when I finished high school, I was barely 16 years old.
I think I just made 17 in February.
But when I went to A&M, I was 19.
I had to lay out two years, which I'm really glad.
I had to wait till my older brother graduated from A&M before I could go.
Because of?
Economics.
Oh, sure.
And Jimmy, too.
Jimmy had to wait a couple years before he went to A&M to let Pete, let Janelle get along in grades before they could help each other with expenses.
But all my schooling was right here in Boulder.
Okay, what were your favorite subjects or topics?
What did you like in school?
Basketball.
Oh, I liked...
Gee, I don't know.
I'm trying to think about it.
History.
History was, I liked history.
And math was not one of my favorites.
I learned to do math and chemistry.
I learned it, but they weren't, chemistry was a, I enjoyed chemistry later on.
But geography and history.
I did very well with those.
I liked those.
What type of student were you?
I was a very conscientious student, which I learned from my daddy.
And then something else, too, I learned.
Not to miss school.
I had an unbelievable attendance record.
Eleven years, almost perfect attendance.
No kidding?
No kidding.
You didn't even get sick?
I don't remember getting sick.
If I did, I was in school.
Because Papa made us go to school.
Boy, if I missed one day of school, if I tried to miss one day of school, I knew what would happen.
But I'm just, I had almost 11 years of perfect attendance going to school.
And same way at A&M.
I didn't miss class.
Just to miss a class, it's unbelievable.
I couldn't believe, I couldn't think about missing a class.
Papa would whip me good.
That brings us to another topic.
What type of discipline did he use on you?
Did he use physical or did he use more psychological methods?
Did he twist your arm physically or mentally?
I hate to use the word physical because it sounds like abuse.
He never abused us, but we were paddled.
Let me put it that way.
We were paddled.
Was he big enough to do it?
No, but he was a man enough to do it.
Papa wasn't too big, wasn't too tall, but yeah, we were disciplined.
Good.
All of us were.
And it was always yes sir and no sir and yes ma'am and no talk back.
Oh, couldn't dare talk back to either one of them.
But Papa...
We'll take discipline action against all of us.
Were you involved, besides basketball, were you involved in other activities in high school?
Yeah, I was a swimmer.
In fact, I was on the swimming team at A&M.
Really?
Yeah.
So you were on the basketball and the swimming team?
Swimming.
I was a diver.
Art Adamson was a coach at A&M.
I went out for breaststroke, and I was pretty good.
But he had two better ones, three better ones, and he says, how about being a diver?
Because he saw me dive, and I said, sure, I'll dive.
And they overlap.
Swimming and basketball overlap.
The seasons did.
And I would play basketball during the week, and then if I had a swim meet, I'd swim.
Coach Corot was my coach, and he said, oh, that's all right.
Go ahead.
I didn't mind.
I didn't try to play baseball or try it.
I just stuck with basketball and swimming in high school.
And then, don't mad, but I was cheerleader three years.
A yell leader?
Yeah, well, at A&M, I mean, at high school.
Oh, really?
Yeah, yell leader, you're right.
But we called them cheerleaders then.
That was my freshman year in high school, ninth, and then the tenth and eleventh.
Really?
I was the first freshman cheerleader Beaumont High's ever had.
I don't know why.
I was a good tumbler.
I could do flips.
Was it unusual to have a male cheerleader back then?
No.
You had two males and two females.
You had four.
And so they decided my freshman year, because I was so small, they'd have five.
And I was a freshman cheerleader.
And I used to do the flips and backflip, frontflips, and handsprings.
And then after that, they had a freshman cheerleader.
We always had five.
Would you consider yourself popular in high school?
Yes, I would.
I was popular.
I was president of the student council.
No kidding?
My senior year in high school.
So, in other words, you were an organizer and somewhat of a leader from an early age.
I would say that.
I mean, not trying to, you know...
In retrospect, yes, I didn't realize it at the time, but I was a leader.
I guess I was.
You were an activist then, really.
Yeah, well, I was captain.
You were in activities.
I was captain of the basketball team, and I was head cheerleader two years, and I was president of the student faculty advisory group in high school.
I wasn't a very high academic.
I made good grades, but I... What do you mean?
B's and C's?
B's and C's.
But I was, yeah, I guess you could say I was very active in high school.
I'm just trying to remember some other things I...
Were all your brothers this active in high school?
Were they all leaders?
They were all pretty well active, right.
They weren't... Janelle was on the baseball team in high school.
Jimmy was a boxer.
And Andrew was on the varsity basketball team with me at the same time.
And he was also a cheerleader, too.
That's right, he was a cheerleader.
Yeah.
And...
So it's a whole family then, of very active people and community-oriented people.
Oh yeah, we were very community-oriented and very active.
And this continued off into our adulthood.
